[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating JUnit dependencies**\n\nI'm trying to figure out if I need the JUnit Platform 6 launcher to use a scanner. The current harness is on platform 1.9, and I see that Spring's TestClassScanner constants might be okay. However, I'm concerned that ClassTemplate isn’t in JUnit 5.9. I may need to add a dependency on JUnit Jupiter 6, but there’s potential for conflict because Spring 7 is built against JUnit Platform 6. I need the right dependencies to manage this.\n\n**Considering JUnit 6 compatibility**\n\nI’m wondering if adding JUnit 6 is supported since Spring Test 7 works with JUnit Jupiter. That seems okay, but I’m concerned about TCK plugin native using JUnit Platform console 1.9—could this break tests with version 6? There's also the issue that JUnit Platform 6 doesn't have a version `6.0.0`, requiring Java 17. I can't skip the compile-time annotation for ClassTemplate. A custom annotation might work, but if the JUnit 5.9 engine can't discover it, that could lead to issues too. I need to add the proper dependency.\n\n**Considering JUnit 6 Test Setup**\n\nI’m thinking about setting up a public API with JUnit 6, possibly without any parameters. I want to ensure the checkstyle has 4 spaces and a max line length of maybe 120. I notice I need a top-level fixture that’s package-private in the same file. It seems that all top-level test classes need to be public, but the fixture might not be a dedicated test. Should I make it a public static nested class? I’m unsure about how JUnit discovers nested classes.\n\n**Exploring JUnit Class Structures**\n\nI'm considering the purpose of TestClassScanner, specifically how it interacts with @Nested test classes. I'm curious about the necessity of a top-level fixture. Can I make it public? However, a Java file can only have one public class. Maybe a separate file, but that might break the rule of one-to-one mapping between dynamic access reports and generated test classes. It seems better to keep everything in the same file with a package-private top-level fixture. This design avoids complications in JUnit's class discovery process.\n\n**Investigating JUnit 5 Discovery**\n\nI'm wondering how JUnit 5 handles static nested test classes. While static nested classes usually aren’t @Nested tests, they can still be selected if annotated correctly. I believe classpath discovery often excludes nested classes by default. Should I be cautious about running tests? It seems like I shouldn’t compile or run them right now. Maybe I can explore source documentation or check upstream test sources for TestClassScanner for better context.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0c3b23dc533ba8d9016a28d37acfc48193a08ce53f364ef32e\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKNOSWw94V68NuCMyN_vWkxS9aR5PxNhFnQOVMVCzKVwXTsEgW9oYY--bmw04nfGRaccUukJqe5BnyiQ2ZJiV5gItaz3dc87cAWP6q6_TcdYFK3QXPDLvrpadNCHdRQdbDGjFvvFAumkle7hUk3B8aSGJ7D8k9-uPSLmT3h8jeCYQcgHIdrbd55Cw9OT1Acg83VadbZzU00nDcIpFTV0r-8vmTGzFCJ7EEV63scaUjQkHZ2rqoQ7EdKo9ptR06mTTfykKsRLN-iXkP-gFUdPAK2xOxlx8EsU_m4Ci0Z7kSJeeJysDrXNXstYoeopuicZrVl01TdI6jeWHFO5fMy5LXyn4wI7W9Rm_E3j_NZEFepb_1h8DNKEivsJLUc5O6FfrX3M0PDTGHYN9Wiy2cTAgNEKo3GSPa1E9S3tH4dCWfDDw5dMrN2MxJilP2N2k2I-JW44t48ZPafc96plHXFdg5GlCfawm4eNNYmvNh4Se7FoYVA2Uib8Sc3lsEQCm3osl3oXcw5l1BzVVt5gvrYFhNcXb_xIajisuiN8062pvndRqb9zeT3Uwh1RYB430JuJY95S2YP7bmacEQmmkiEVv8kO77cF64SWiMUTmSVauAmWk1kMQoJlxsDSaun6NKWoDX1uCTbse4VwWXalGA29cfhRtozUIbiaPfnTBPOsre-JmFCu_R7nl0xp6HFXl3-FA8FKsm_WCrzS_uSEpDu2XzxhEBbWzcczq6Y8v6mVWsAC0ttxRAEJ5AGYYLHI2wKdxc8oGJDXy2lHBTA1h0TcvGe9xtYzrXDkcDVgElDE-_IQXoonlN378IiPxpz55WK-y6S9TV_0S01pz53LPsyu8MVbCJeYIME3WSyLmviwp7K86B7zQK2-p3vvY_qrOfPCpBtOpPhQwvYSjGurM_OR0yW3-naAT9VEQd48g8VXNb0IvRwn3rJwtGdjh3majak1Re87cg6aJY3Ty_wWuIEmC6RJHa4kHob3owiBKKuCnnqgyq0aExJAxym36MHc1pH-b_7SVv7smbbCimDwuw836Pt3DW9B-4kFT48p4kvB2qloURJDxsQGSgO-XX5DL9sV8OztURDwNxrUMPfd8PSwldkRSZ_T458OFLp