s.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring JUnit Class Structures**\\n\\nI'm considering the purpose of TestClassScanner, specifically how it interacts with @Nested test classes. I'm curious about the necessity of a top-level fixture. Can I make it public? However, a Java file can only have one public class. Maybe a separate file, but that might break the rule of one-to-one mapping between dynamic access reports and generated test classes. It seems better to keep everything in the same file with a package-private top-level fixture. This design avoids complications in JUnit's class discovery process.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating JUnit 5 Discovery**\\n\\nI'm wondering how JUnit 5 handles static nested test classes. While static nested classes usually aren’t @Nested tests, they can still be selected if annotated correctly. I believe classpath discovery often excludes nested classes by default. Should I be cautious about running tests? It seems like I shouldn’t compile or run them right now. Maybe I can explore source documentation or check upstream test sources for TestClassScanner for better context.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_LKchT7CWvg3A0b6ZX2YZNG3p|fc_0c3b23dc533ba8d9016a28d392ed08819392d447a15a10de2c", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find ../../source_context/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0 -path '*test*' -type f | grep TestClassScanner | head -20 && rg \"ParameterizedClass|ClassTemplate|collectNested\" ../../source_context/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0 -n | head -50"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1300, "output": 1078, "cacheRead": 33792, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 36170, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781060473658, "responseId": "resp_0c3b23dc533ba8d9016a28d37a247881939a47dcb8017a92c5"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "tool